NAME: Olentangy Indian Caverns
DESCRIPTION: Formed millions of years ago by the tremendous force of an underground river, the Olentangy Indian Caverns offer an exciting adventure. Descend 105 feet below the Earth's surface and visit a place where time stands still!

NAME: Hanby House
DESCRIPTION: This is the home of Benjamin Russell Hanby, a composer of music who lived during the mid and late 19th century. By preserving this house, visitors catch a glimpse into the livelihood of people during the 19th century.

NAME: Thurber House
DESCRIPTION: James Thurber was a famous humorist during the early and mid 20th century. With the preservation of his estate, writings and personal belongings and with the creation of the Thurber Center, the Thurber House is an interactive and exciting experience!

NAME: Kelton House
DESCRIPTION: The Kelton House Museum and Garden interprets urban life and the decorative arts in Columbus, Ohio during the second half of the 19th century, largely through the collection of the Sophia and Fernando Cortez Kelton family.

NAME: Ohio Historical Society
DESCRIPTION: The foundation in understanding Ohio's past has numerous historical displays from all over Ohio and helps promote other historical sites in Ohio.

NAME: John Clark House
DESCRIPTION: The historic home of Gahanna's founder, John Clark,  is decorated with donations from the descendents of John Clark. Donations consist of artifacts from the 1800's.

NAME: Log House
DESCRIPTION: Moved from the outskirts of Gahanna to the Historical Society's designated property, the Log Cabin has become a staple for the Historic Society. Created in 1840 by David Shull, the house is now used to show what life was like in the 1800's.

NAME: Lilystone B&B
DESCRIPTION: This bed and breakfast is located in historic Gahanna and has been decorated in the classic Victorian home style. 4 rooms available.

NAME: The Doll Museum
DESCRIPTION: This museum has an amazing array of dolls in tis collection, most notably, a Hinamatsuri piece presented to the city of Worthington from Sayama, Japan.

NAME: Orton Geological Museum
DESCRIPTION: The Orton Geological Museum has an array of amazing artifacts; from dinosaur bones, to meteorites, to flourescent minerals, this museum has it all!

NAME: Ohio Craft Museum
DESCRIPTION: Crafts, crafts, crafts! This museum is soley devoted to the collection and appreciation of fine crafts. The museum offers exhibitions and even services for artisits!

NAME: Heritage Museum
DESCRIPTION: Located in an Italianate mansion that was built in 1852 and was once the Civil War home of a former Ohio governor, this museum makes use of the history of Kappa Kappa Gamma to trace the changing role of women in higher education throughout history.

NAME: Northwest Village At Weaver Park
DESCRIPTION: The scenic run of buildings shows what life was like between the years of 1850 to 1900.

NAME: Motts Military Museum
DESCRIPTION: The Motts Museum attempts to educate the public on the importance of America’s military past through the documentation, collection, interpretation, and preservation of tangible artifacts and personal stories of the men and women who served and are s*

NAME: Mid-Ohio Historical Doll & Toy Muse
DESCRIPTION: Doll and toy collectors have a place to visit now! This museum has classic dolls and toys to more modern types of dolls and toys. Activities range from tours to interactive luncheons!

NAME: Early Television Museum
DESCRIPTION: This museum has all sorts of early television history, including old mechanical and electronic televisions from the U.S. and Europe, early TV ads, Web pages devoted to TV history, and more!

NAME: Motorcycle Hall Of Fame Museum
DESCRIPTION: Ranging from motorcycle exhibits to Hall of Fame induction ceremonies, the Motorcycle Hall of Fame has it all for fans of the “iron horse.”

NAME: Moose Lodge Museum
DESCRIPTION: There are only two Moose Lodge Museums in the country...and one sits rights in Gahanna! This museum is full of historic pieces of the Moose Lodge history, displaying their charity and fellowship.

NAME: Fletcher Coffman Homestead
DESCRIPTION: With renovations, the Flecther-Coffman Homestead has become perfect example of how people lived in Central Ohio during the 1800's. The property holds farms tools, paintings, and furniture from the period.

NAME: Harrison House
DESCRIPTION: Experience one of Columbus’ unique lodging accommodations! Nestled in downtown Columbus, this house was built in 1890 and now serves as a bed and breakfast.

NAME: COSI
DESCRIPTION: COSI is a long standing tradition in the Central Ohio area and has seen nearly 19 million visitors since the doors opened in 1964! COSI shows science in a fun and educational manner that the entire family can enjoy!

NAME: Columbus Museum Of Art
DESCRIPTION: The Columbus Museum of Art houses an outstanding collection of late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century American and European modern art. Constantly cycling through exhibits, the museum continues to have new pieces of art for your viewing pleasu*

NAME: Columbus Fire House Museum
DESCRIPTION: Through a collection of hand-drawn, horse-drawn and motorized fire apparatus, visitors will be able to retrace the steps of firefighters and learn about their day-to-day lives in the engine house, we get to learn about the price firefighters have pa*

NAME: The Orange House
DESCRIPTION: The Orange Johnson house is the only home of its era standing on its original foundation in Franklin Count and now serves to show Ohioans a piece of their history and culture.

NAME: Powell-Liberty Historical Society
DESCRIPTION: The job of the Powell-Liberty Historical Society is to preserve and protect historical artifacts, from buildings to small documents that help to tell the tale of this quaint and adorable town.

NAME: Richard M Ross Museum
DESCRIPTION: The Richard M. Ross museum of art houses local collections and the collection of Ohio Wesleyan University.

NAME: Granville Life-Style Museum
DESCRIPTION: This museum puts on the display the rich history and culture of Eastern Ohio and helps the visitor to gain a better understanding of this part of Ohio.

NAME: Greater Buckeye Lake Museum
DESCRIPTION: The Buckeye Lake Museum was opened in 1998 and has had 17,000 visitors pass through the doors! Artifacts range from documents, to pieces of pottery, to a massive old fashioned tour boat.

NAME: National Heisey Glass Museum
DESCRIPTION: Visitors are treated to breathtaking arrangements of Heisey glassware featuring hundreds of patterns and all known colors. Elegant cuttings, etchings and engravings, as well as experimental pieces, can also be seen.

NAME: Robbins Hunter Museum
DESCRIPTION: The nationally acclaimed Greek Revival house was built in 1842 by Alfred Avery, one of the founders of Granville Ohio. The house was added to over the years and now has 27 rooms of which 14 are open to the public.

NAME: Sherwood Davidson Museum
DESCRIPTION: This museum is one of the finest examples of Federal Architecture in the Ohio Valley.  Built in 1827 Buckingham Sherwood designed the house with all the specifications of yesteryear.

NAME: Webb House Museum
DESCRIPTION: This museum house is a fine example of architecture from the early 20th century. Frank Camden Webb filled the house with luxurious goods and artifacts.

NAME: Ashville City Museum
DESCRIPTION: Built out of the imminent demise of the railroad station, artifacts were found in the attic, much to the amazement of everyone! What is now intimately called "Ohio's Small-Town Museum" allows for visitors to gain a unique historical portrayal of the*

NAME: Ted Lewis Museum
DESCRIPTION: Famous jazz musician, Ted Lewis, changed the idea of what jazz could be, pushing the music and the stage presence of contemporary jazz. This museum shows his life's story and his wonderful ability to play jazz clarinet through videos and recordings.

NAME: Barber Museum
DESCRIPTION: This one of a kind and truly unique museum shows the history behind the baber in America. Tools date back to the 1700's and displays a day when barbers were surgeons and dentists!

NAME: Georgian Museum
DESCRIPTION: The Georgian House was owned by a Samuel Maccracken circa 1832 and is now in the hands of the Fairfield Heritage Association. Rebuilt and remodeled to its original grandeur, this magnificent house shows an amazing history of Ohio.

NAME: Ohio Glass Museum
DESCRIPTION: Gorgeous! Breathtaking! The pieces that live in these halls displays the utter beauty of glass making, Travelling exhibits and pieces owned by the museum are on constant display.
